  <section id="installation">
	<div class="page-header"><h3>Installation</h3><hr class="notop"></div>
<p>
	You will only have to need the following:</p>
<ol>
	<li>
		Extract the content from aDBstract folder into your public html folder&nbsp;</li>
	<li>
		Open aDBstract/com/selfdeve/adbstract/ConnectionManager.php</li>
	<li>
		Configure your own access database parameters, make sure they are valid</li>
	<li>
		Power On your locals servers, apache and mysql</li>
	<li>
		Enter the following url in your browser:&nbsp;http://localhost/aDBstract/WebContent/index.php</li>
	<li>
		You must see the aDBstract index page</li>
</ol>
<p>
	&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	<a href="assets/images/image_2.jpg"><img alt="" src="assets/images/image_2.jpg"></a></p>
<p>
	&nbsp;</p>
</section>
<section id="run_adbstract">
	<div class="page-header"><h3>Run aDBstract</h3><hr class="notop"></div>
<p>
	Follow these steps to create the database Bean Class and Controller Class:</p>
<ol>
	<li>
		Click the Get tables button</li>
	<li>
		Select the table &nbsp;that you want to abstract for.</li>
	<li>
		Set the class name if you want, by default Bean.php and Controller.php files will be created.</li>
	<li>
		Click the Run aDBstract! button</li>
	<li>
		Check the GeneratedClases folder, now you can export the files.</li>
</ol>
<p>
	&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	<img alt="" src="assets/images/image_1.jpg"></p>
</section>
<section id="how_to_use">
	<div class="page-header"><h3>How to use</h3><hr class="notop"></div>
<p>
	Follow thes steps to use the aDBstract generated clases:</p>
<ol>
	<li>
		Initalize a PDO object: $pdo = new PDO(&quot;my conn params&quot;, &quot;myuser&quot;, &quot;mypassword&quot;);</li>
	<li>
		Initialize a new Object of the database Controller class: $controller = new Controller($pdo);</li>
	<li>
		Initializa some new Object of the database Bean class: $bean = new Bean();</li>
	<li>
		Set data to the Bean Object: $bean-&gt;setField1(&quot;data&quot;); $bean-&gt;setField7(&quot;data7&quot;);</li>
	<li>
		Run the Controller method you want: &nbsp;$controller-&gt;executeSelect($bean);</li>
	<li>
		Read the returned data from your database</li>
</ol>
<ul>
	<li>
		executeSelect method: returns an array of Bean Object.</li>
	<li>
		executeInsert method: returns the number of inserted rows.</li>
	<li>
		executeUpdate method: returns the number of affected rows.</li>
	<li>
		executeDelete method: returns the number of deleted rows.</li>
</ul>
<p>
	&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	Check the <a href="#options">#options</a>&nbsp; section to extend the functionality features</p>
<p>
	&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	&nbsp;</p>
</section>
<section id="options">
	<div class="page-header"><h3>Options</h3><hr class="notop"></div>
<p>
	You can use the followings options:</p>
<ul>
	<li>
		LIMIT clause</li>
	<li>
		OFFSET clause</li>
	<li>
		ORDER by clause</li>
</ul>
<p>
	&nbsp;</p>
<ol>
	<li>
		Using ORDER BY clause:</li>
</ol>
<ul style="margin-left: 40px;">
	<li>
		Set $controller-&gt;setOrderBy($array), $array must be an array like:</li>
</ul>
<p style="margin-left: 120px;">
	$array = [</p>
<p style="margin-left: 160px;">
	&quot;myField1Name&quot;: &quot;ASC&quot;,</p>
<p style="margin-left: 160px;">
	&quot;myField4Name&quot;: &quot;DESC&quot;</p>
<p style="margin-left: 120px;">
	]</p>
<ul>
	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">
		Run your select query</li>
</ul>
<p style="margin-left: 40px;">
	&nbsp;</p>
<p style="margin-left: 40px;">
	2.- Using LIMIT and OFFSET:</p>
<ul>
	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">
		Set $controller-&gt;setLimit($int), $int is an integer number representing the LIMIT clause value</li>
	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">
		You can optionally set a OFFSET clause if you want: $controller-&gt;setOffset($offst), $offst is an integer representing the OFFSET clause value.</li>
</ul>
</section>



